To investigate how a self-perceived body differed from the actual body (Objective 1), the researchers needed a standard to rate actual body size and shapes. Textile/Clothing Technology Corporation (2006) categorized age groups into five categories (18–25, 26–35, 36–45, 46–55, and over 56) for SizeUSA data. To match the subject population, the researchers selected 2,981 women aged 18–35 from SizeUSA data as a data set to calculate overall missy size population sizes and shapes. To eliminate obese women outside the size range of our study, the researchers first calculated the percentiles of BMI, waist girth, and hip girth measurements. A BMI value of 30 (classified as the “obese” category provided by National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute
1
) was positioned between the 75th and the 90th percentile for the SizeUSA data (Table 1). The researchers compared waist girth and hip girth measurements for size 20 (the maximum size) of the sizing standard ASTM 5585-95 with the girth measurements for the SizeUSA data (Table 1). Both waist girth and hip girth measurements for Size 20 were positioned between the 75th and the 90th percentile for SizeUSA data. In consideration of the distribution of all three of the values, the researchers selected only women (n = 2,682) within the 90th percentile of BMI (34.1) for this study to eliminate obese women. Next, the researchers removed outliers (defined as any subject with body measurements that exceeded 3 times the standard deviation from the mean for measurements used in the study). As the number (n = 194) of outliers was less than 10% of the total, the researchers considered that the final data set (n = 2,488) was appropriate for analysis.
